(I still wonder if Chanter wasn't really my fav class...) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ugnosisgnome.showPublicProfile?language=EN>GnosisGnome</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/20/02 12:59:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm44.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=64.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Mage power!</span><hr size=1> I'm nearly the only mage in my guild, and have been so for quite some time, so my experience might be idiosyncratic to me. However, lemme tell you about my experience.<br>
<br>
I'm in my 30's, and I never have any trouble with finding groups. In the old days, folks didn't want mages in dungeons, because their pets would wander off and draw a bunch of aggroed nasties back. However, a little while back, they finally changed it so that the pets do not pace. The result is that most of the time a pet is reliable in a dungeon, with the exception of a few with really odd pathing (such as Permafrost, where my pet got two whole groups wiped out by the entire frost goblin nation by following a goblin along some weird pathing -- sigh). And in outdoor zones, the pet is nearly always reliable.<br>
<br>
My lead tank loves having my pet around. First, in normal combat, the pet acts as an &quot;assistant tank,&quot; taking a little heat off the tank. The pet sits there and constantly nickels &amp; dimes the mob. If you've cast the right kind of pet, that can be very helpful.<br>
<br>
Also, when things get rough (especially in a smaller group without a healer, or with an OOM healer), the lead tank can step back and let the pet hold the mob. In that case, it is your job as mage to act as a pet cleric. Remember, you aren't trying to save the pet in that situation -- you are trying to keep the mob occupied for a bit while the tank frantically binds his wounds (with the bandages you summoned, by the way) and the healers try to med up enough to lay another heal on the lead tank. <br>
<br>
When things are completely desperate and everyone is making a run for the zone wall, the mage should be the last to zone. Usually, the mage is at full HP or close to it (since the lesser nukes of the mage don't draw as much aggro). Run right to the edge of the zone, lay out all the rest of your mana healing your pet, and try to get your pet to hold the mob until everyone else is safely out of the zone. Make sure, however, you are only a step or two from the edge of the zone wall, so the tank or healer doesn't feel obligated to stay behind and help. And, by the way, every so often you get really lucky, and your pet manages to kill off the mob after everyone but you has zoned. My advice in that situation -- wait for everyone else to zone back in, then loot the mob -- you'll be a hero, trust me.<br>
<br>
Outside of pet handling, a mage has got three basic jobs. The first is summoning -- and don't let anyone tell you this isn't valuable. At lower levels, it saves A LOT of money. My lead tank actually bought my summon bandages spell, and he calculated that it paid for itself with free bandages in two days. At higher levels, you get some really nice items -- the focus items are great, and at the mid ranges everyone loves the elemental defender -- mostly because it equips on the back, a slot not well-filled for most non-twinks, like you'll find on FV. By the way, in any guild, you are going to be loved by the younger guildies -- because when most of them are still fighting naked with a rusty dagger, you can summon up a full suit of armor and some nice weapons. A mage who uses his summoning for philanthropy rather than for profit is beloved everywhere he goes -- and especially on FV.<br>
<br>
The second job is damage shielding. The mage DS is nice, though like with most DS's works better on mobs that hit a lot for a little damage, than for mobs that hit less for a greater degree of damage -- like say a giant. The DS doesn't last long, though, so you've got to pay close attention to keep it up. I usually try to throw it on the puller just before he goes out to pull, and then throw it on others as soon as the mob arrives. One caution -- the DS draws aggro, so don't cast it on anyone who you don't want aggroed -- like a wizard.<br>
<br>
The third and final job is nuking. The mage has respectable nukes, but they are lesser than those of a wizard. A good nuker (of any class) learns that nuking involves as much strategy as any other part of the game. Knowing who to nuke and when makes you more mana efficient, and in certain situations can mean the difference between life and death for your party.<br>
<br>
One final note -- don't let anyone give you grief about your race/class combo. This is Firiona Vie, the roleplaying preferred server, not kEwL d00dz central. Don't worry about the stats and such -- if you've got a good character concept, and you have fun, then play it! And while we've got our share of &quot;Woot! Plz platz thnx!&quot; I think you'll find on FV you are far more likely to find a group based on your personality (and your character's personality) than you would on some other servers.<br>
<br>
By the way, if you need any help, look me up. I'm always willing to help out a fellow student of the eldritch mysteries.<br>
<br>
Yours,<br>
Gnosis Bunglefoot<br>
Ledenyetz Troupe<br>
30-something Mage<br>
